[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    505[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    506[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Performance benchmarks:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    507[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    508[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Metric | Typical Value |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    509[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |--------|---------------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    510[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Feature engineering (500K patients) | 15-25 minutes (Glue, 10 DPUs) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    511[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | K-means training (500K patients, k=5) | 5-10 minutes (ml.m5.large) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    512[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | End-to-end pipeline | 45-60 minutes |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    513[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Silhouette score | 0.35-0.50 (typical for healthcare data) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    514[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Segment stability (month-to-month) | 85-92% of patients stay in same segment |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    515[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | DynamoDB lookup latency | <5ms per patient |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    516[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Cost per monthly run (500K patients) | $10-20 |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    517[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    518[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Where it struggles:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    519[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    520[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Patients with very few encounters (1-2 per year) produce sparse feature vectors that cluster unreliably. Consider a minimum encounter threshold (e.g., 3+ encounters in the window) or a separate "insufficient data" category.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    521[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - New members without 12 months of history get incomplete profiles. Use a shorter window or assign them to a "new member" holding segment until enough data accumulates.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    522[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Populations with extreme bimodal distributions (e.g., Medicaid populations with very high and very low utilizers and little in between) may produce segments that are really just "high" and "low" with noise in between.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    523[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Seasonal patterns (flu season, open enrollment) can distort features if your window doesn't cover a full year.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    524[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    525[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    526[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    527[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Honest Take
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    528[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    529[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Utilization pattern segmentation is one of those problems that's genuinely satisfying to solve. The first time you show a population health director five distinct behavioral segments with clear profiles and they say "yes, I recognize these patients," it feels like magic. It's not magic. It's k-means on well-engineered features. But the impact is real.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    530[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    531[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The part that surprised me: the feature engineering matters 10x more than the algorithm choice. I've seen teams spend weeks tuning hyperparameters and trying fancy algorithms (DBSCAN, spectral clustering, deep embedding clustering) when the real problem was that their features were just "count of encounters by type." Add regularity, diversity, trend, and ratio features and suddenly basic k-means produces clinically meaningful segments.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    532[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    533[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The silhouette scores will be lower than you expect. Healthcare data is messy, patients don't form neat spherical clusters, and there are always patients on the boundaries between segments. A silhouette score of 0.4 is actually quite good for this domain. Don't chase a score of 0.8; you'll overfit to noise.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    534[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    535[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The political challenge is real. When you show leadership that 4% of their population is in the "Complex/Crisis-Driven" segment and those 8,000 patients account for 35% of total cost, the immediate reaction is "great, let's do intensive care management for all of them." But intensive care management doesn't work for patients whose primary drivers are housing instability or untreated addiction. The segmentation tells you *who* to focus on. It doesn't tell you *what* to do. That requires a second layer of analysis within each segment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    536[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    537[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Refresh cadence matters more than initial accuracy. A segmentation that's 90% accurate but refreshed monthly is more useful than one that's 95% accurate but run once a year. Patients move between segments. Catching those transitions early is where the value lives.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    538[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    539[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    540[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    541[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Variations and Extensions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    542[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    543[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Soft clustering with Gaussian Mixture Models.** Instead of assigning each patient to exactly one segment, use GMMs to produce probability distributions. "This patient is 60% Rising Risk and 40% Fragmented Care." Soft assignments are more honest (patients rarely fit perfectly into one box) and enable more nuanced intervention targeting. The trade-off: harder to operationalize in downstream systems that expect a single segment label.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    544[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    545[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Temporal trajectory clustering.** Instead of clustering on a single time-window snapshot, cluster on the *sequence* of utilization patterns over time. Use dynamic time warping or sequence clustering to find patients with similar trajectories. This identifies patients who are on the same path, even if they're at different points along it. Significantly more complex to implement but powerful for early intervention.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    546[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    547[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Segment-specific predictive models.** Once you have stable segments, train separate predictive models within each segment. A readmission risk model trained on "Fragmented Care" patients will perform better than a one-size-fits-all model because the risk factors are different for that population. This is the "segment, then predict" pattern and it consistently outperforms global models.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    548[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    549[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    550[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    551[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Related Recipes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    552[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    553[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 6.1 (Geographic Patient Clustering):** Uses similar clustering infrastructure but on geographic features; can be combined with utilization segmentation for geo-behavioral segments
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    554[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 6.4 (Disease Severity Stratification):** Clusters within a specific disease population rather than across the full membership; complementary to utilization segmentation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    555[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 7.1 (Readmission Risk Scoring):** Consumes segment assignments as features in predictive models; "segment, then predict" pattern
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    556[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 4.6 (Care Gap Prioritization):** Uses segment assignments to prioritize which care gaps to address first for which patients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    557[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    558[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
